obo:ECO_0005589  a  owl:Class .

gomodel:SYNGO_1869  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: mTOR siRNA transfection reduced mTOR (Fig. 8I) and phospho-p70S6K (Fig. 8J) in dendrites upon BDNF treatment in cortical cultures. Figure 8L shows the intensity of red fluorescence, which reflects phospho-S6K signal, in each dendrite that is measured.\n\nIn Figure 9 the authors analysed phosph-4EBP levels in isolated dendrites. Even in isolated dendrites, BDNF increased and rapamycin decreased the levels of phosphorylated 4EBP (Fig. 9A-F), indicating the local activation of mTOR-dependent translation in dendrites.\n\n14/11/2017 Pim\n- The BDNF-induced activation of protein translation is rapamycin-sensitive. Rapamycin is an antagonist of mTOR.\n- The phospho state of 4EBP1 is used as a readout of the efffect of mTOR on protein translation.\\\n- Literal: \"BDNF increased protein synthesis in the synaptoneurosomes, a concentrated fraction of presynaptic and postsynaptic components prepared from rat brain\" --> shows synaptic context. Experimental description: Cortical neuronal cultured prepared at E17 and used for experiments at DIV10-14\n(From Takei et al., 1998)\n\n14/11/2017 Pim\n- Species of the neuronal culture not stated in the paper. Species traced back to rat via PMID:15525761 referenced in the M&M section: \"Briefly, cerebral cortices were removed from 17-day-old embryonic rat fetuses and dissociated using trypsin/DNase I.\"" ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-9848-0262" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-4419-210X" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-1190-4481" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2094-7491" ;
        dc:date           "2017-11-14" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_BP_1869" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10116" .

